The description here given oi the Roman contract system—ii we may use that expression to indicate the aggregate oi actionable agreements-is somewhat misleading. It must not be supposed that in the time of Justinian, or even oi Gaius, no agreement was ground to support an action which was neither expressed in the form of stipulation, nor belonged to one or other oi the classes ol Real and Consensual contracts. There had been a considerable advance in two directions since the time when usage had restricted the term ‘contract' to denote the four classes oi agreement errumerated in Title 13. Between the establishment ol the Empire and the age oi the last great classical jurists the principle oi the Real contracte had received a great development by the recognition oi the rule, that where one party to any bilateral agreement whatsoever had performed what he had undertahen, he had always a remedy by action to enforce performance by the other.
